<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-917-402  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 917 402.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 27 1989 v23 n48 p47(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Local-area networks to put on laser light show.andO;(Telecommunications management Corp. Lace LAN-to-LAN product)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wexler, Joanie M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telecommunications Management Corp announces the Lace L00-19Token-Ring System, a new LAN-to-LAN product which uses lasertechnology to achieve high throughput and reduce communicationsbottlenecks.andP;  The Lace system connects Token Ring local-areanetworks at their full 4M-bps data rate and offers superiorreliability because lasers are not as distance-constrained asinfrared waves.andP;  It consists of two pairs of repeaters at thephysical layer; a front-end unit interfaces directly to the TokenRing at each network location, connecting to a rooftop lasertransceiver via cable.andP;  Telecommunications Management is targetingapplications in heavily built-up environments where obtaining amicrowave license is difficult; lasers do not require FCClicensing.andP;  The company admits that lasers, which have aone-kilometer transmission limit, do not travel as far asmicrowaves.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Telecommunications Management Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Lace L00-19 Token-Ring System (Computer communications equipment)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     ConnectivityLasersFiber OpticsThroughput.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>